# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anticucho
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:anticucho/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] Chili pepper varieties in the *C. baccatum* species have white or cream-colored flowers and typically have a green or gold corolla.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] The flowers are either insect or self-pollinated.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] The fruit pods of the *baccatum* species have been cultivated into a wide variety of shapes and sizes, unlike other *capsicum* species, which tend to have a characteristic shape.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] Unlike a *Capsicum frutescens* plant, the pods typically hang down and can have a citrus or fruity flavor.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] *pendulum*) is the domesticated pepper of choice of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Chile.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] The Moche culture often represented fruits and vegetables in their art, including *ají amarillo* peppers.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] South American farmers also grow *C. baccatum* as ornamental plants for export.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] The *C. baccatum* species, notably the ***ají amarillo chili***, has its origins in ancient Peru and across the Andean region of South America.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] It is typically associated with Peruvian cuisine, and is considered part of its condiment trinity together with red onion and coriander.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] *Ají amarillo* literally means "yellow chili"; however, the yellow color appears only when cooked, as the mature pods are bright orange.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] The Ají Amarillo pepper has been named the "Flavor of the Year" for 2025 by McCormick & Company, a prominent spice company.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] This pepper is expected to see a 59% increase in menu appearances over the next four years.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] Some form of the word *ají* has been used since approximately 4600 BCE.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] It was first used in the protolanguage Otomanguean.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] It then spread along with the Capsicum fruit from Central and South America to other pepper-growing regions.
[src:anticucho/ají-pepper] *Capsicum baccatum* is still referred to as *ají*, while other peppers are referred to as "pepper" via the Spanish conquistadors noting the similarity in heat sensation to black pepper.
[src:anticucho/aloo-chaat] It can be served as a snack, a side dish or a light meal.
[src:anticucho/aloo-chaat] It is made from boiled and fried cubed potatoes served with chat masala.
[src:anticucho/aloo-chaat] It is a versatile dish that has many regional variations.
[src:anticucho/aloo-chaat] The word *alu* means potatoes in Hindi and the word *chat* is derived from the Hindi word *chatna*, which means 'tasting'.
[src:anticucho/aloo-chaat] Thus, 'alu chat' means a savory potato snack.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] Because of the broad geographical distribution of Indian people throughout the world, a number of variations on this dish exist.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] In Maharashtra, a popular version of aloo tikki is served with a spicy curry and various chutneys.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] It is called ragda pattice and is sold at various chaat stalls throughout the city and especially on Chowpatti Beach.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] The aloo tikki in this region is made of mainly locally grown spices such as turmeric, whereas in Bangalore, more coriander is used.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] In the United Kingdom, vegetable tikki is available from delicatessen counters at various shops.
[src:anticucho/aloo-tikki] Some North Indian dhabas or café-style eateries will sandwich the aloo in bread.
[src:anticucho/andes] The **Andes** (/ˈændiːz/ *AN-deez*), **Andes Mountains** or **Andean Mountain Range** (Spanish: *Cordillera de los Andes*; Quechua: *Anti*) are the longest continental mountain range in the world, forming a continuous highland along the western edge of South America.
[src:anticucho/andes] The range is 8,900 kilometres (5,500 mi) long and 200 to 700 kilometres (120 to 430 mi) wide (widest between 18°S and 20°S latitude) and has an average height of about 4,000 metres (13,000 ft).
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes extend from south to north through seven South American countries: Argentina, Chile, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, and Venezuela.
[src:anticucho/andes] Along their length, the Andes are split into several ranges, separated by intermediate depressions.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are the location of several high plateaus—some of which host major cities such as Arequipa, Bogotá, Cali, Medellín, El Alto, La Paz, Mérida, Santiago and Sucre.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Altiplano Plateau is the world's second highest after the Tibetan Plateau.
[src:anticucho/andes] These ranges are in turn grouped into three major divisions based on climate: the Tropical Andes, the Dry Andes, and the Wet Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are the highest mountain range outside of Asia.
[src:anticucho/andes] The range's highest peak, Argentina's Aconcagua, rises to an elevation of about 6,961 metres (22,838 ft) above sea level.
[src:anticucho/andes] The peak of Chimborazo in the Ecuadorian Andes is farther from the Earth's center than any other location on the Earth's surface, due to the equatorial bulge resulting from the Earth's rotation.
[src:anticucho/andes] The world's highest volcanoes are in the Andes, including Ojos del Salado on the Chile–Argentina border, which rises to 6,893 metres (22,615 ft).
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are also part of the American Cordillera, a chain of mountain ranges (cordillera) that consists of an almost continuous sequence of mountain ranges that form the western "backbone" of the Americas and Antarctica.
[src:anticucho/andes] The etymology of the word *Andes* has been debated.
[src:anticucho/andes] The majority consensus is that it derives from the Quechua word *anti* "east" as in *Antisuyu* (Quechua for "east region"), one of the four regions of the Inca Empire.
[src:anticucho/andes] Others suggest that it is in fact from the word *anta* (meaning *copper*) of the older Aymara language.
[src:anticucho/andes] The term *cordillera* comes from the Spanish word *cordel* "rope" and is used as a descriptive name for several contiguous sections of the Andes, as well as the entire Andean range, and the combined mountain chain along the western part of the North and South American continents.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes mountain range, the longest continental mountain system in the world, extends approximately 7,000 km (4,300 mi) along the western edge of South America, spanning seven countries.
[src:anticucho/andes] Its width varies from 200 km (120 mi) to 700 km (430 mi), encompassing a series of parallel cordilleras, high plateaus, and deep intermontane valleys.
[src:anticucho/andes] Prominent peaks such as Aconcagua at 6,961 metres (22,838 feet) in Argentina, Huascarán at 6,768 metres (22,205 feet) in Peru, and Illimani 6,438 metres (21,122 feet) in Bolivia illustrate the extreme elevations and rugged relief that define the range.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes encompass a wide variety of climatic and ecological zones, ranging from humid cloud forests on the eastern slopes to the arid high plains of the Altiplano and the glaciated summits of the southern Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] These sharp environmental gradients have strongly influenced human settlement and the development of major highland cities such as Bogotá, Cusco, La Paz and Quito.
[src:anticucho/andes] At the northern end of the Andes, the separate Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta range is often, but not always, treated as part of the Northern Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are an orogenic belt of mountains along the Pacific Ring of Fire, a zone of volcanic activity that encompasses the Pacific rim of the Americas as well as the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are the result of tectonic plate processes extending during the Mesozoic and Tertiary eras, caused by the subduction of oceanic crust beneath the South American Plate as the Nazca Plate and South American Plate converge.
[src:anticucho/andes] These processes were accelerated by the effects of climate.
[src:anticucho/andes] As the uplift of the Andes created a rain shadow on the western fringes of Chile, ocean currents and prevailing winds carried moisture away from the Chilean coast.
[src:anticucho/andes] This caused some areas of the subduction zone to be sediment-starved, which in turn prevented the subducting plate from having a well lubricated surface.
[src:anticucho/andes] These factors increased the rate of contractional coastal uplift in the Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The main cause of the rise of the Andes is the contraction of the western rim of the South American Plate due to the subduction of the Nazca Plate and the Antarctic Plate.
[src:anticucho/andes] To the east, the Andes range is bounded by several sedimentary basins, such as the Orinoco Basin, the Amazon Basin, the Madre de Dios Basin, and the Gran Chaco, that separate the Andes from the ancient cratons in eastern South America.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the south, the Andes share a long boundary with the former Patagonia Terrane.
[src:anticucho/andes] To the west, the Andes end at the Pacific Ocean, although the Peru–Chile Trench can be considered their ultimate western limit.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andean orogen has a series of bends or oroclines.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Bolivian Orocline is a seaward-concave bending in the coast of South America and the Andes Mountains at about 18° S.
[src:anticucho/andes] At this point, the orientation of the Andes turns from northwest in Peru to south in Chile and Argentina.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andean segments north and south of the Orocline have been rotated 15° counter-clockwise to 20° clockwise respectively.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Bolivian Orocline area overlaps with the area of the maximum width of the Altiplano Plateau, and according to Isacks (1988) the Orocline is related to crustal shortening.
[src:anticucho/andes] The specific point at 18° S where the coastline bends is known as the Arica Elbow.
[src:anticucho/andes] Further south lies the Maipo Orocline, a more subtle orocline between 30° S and 38°S with a seaward-concave break in the trend at 33° S.
[src:anticucho/andes] Near the southern tip of the Andes lies the Patagonian Orocline.
[src:anticucho/andes] The formation of the modern Andes began with the events of the Triassic, when Pangaea began the breakup that resulted in developing several rifts.
[src:anticucho/andes] The development continued through the Jurassic Period.
[src:anticucho/andes] It was during the Cretaceous Period that the Andes began to take their present form, by the uplifting, faulting, and folding of sedimentary and metamorphic rocks of the ancient cratons to the east.
[src:anticucho/andes] The rise of the Andes has not been constant, as different regions have had different degrees of tectonic stress, uplift, and erosion.
[src:anticucho/andes] Across the 1,000-kilometer-wide (620 mi) Drake Passage lie the mountains of the Antarctic Peninsula south of the Scotia Plate, which appear to be a continuation of the Andes chain.
[src:anticucho/andes] The far east regions of the Andes experience a series of changes resulting from the Andean orogeny.
[src:anticucho/andes] Parts of the Sunsás Orogen in Amazonian craton disappeared from the surface of the earth, being overridden by the Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Sierras de Córdoba, where the effects of the ancient Pampean orogeny can be observed, owe their modern uplift and relief to the Andean orogeny in the Tertiary.
[src:anticucho/andes] Further south in southern Patagonia, the onset of the Andean orogeny caused the Magallanes Basin to evolve from being an extensional back-arc basin in the Mesozoic to being a contractional foreland basin in the Cenozoic.
[src:anticucho/andes] Many high-magnitude earthquakes have been recorded in the region, such as the 2010 Maule earthquake (M8.8), the 2015 Illapel earthquake (M8.2), and the 1960 Valdivia earthquake (M9.5), which as of 2024 was the strongest ever recorded on seismometers.
[src:anticucho/andes] The amount, magnitude, and type of seismic activity varies greatly along the subduction zone.
[src:anticucho/andes] These differences are due to a wide range of factors, including friction between the plates, angle of subduction, buoyancy of the subducting plate, rate of subduction, and hydration value of the mantle material.
[src:anticucho/andes] The highest rate of seismic activity is observed in the central portion of the boundary, between 33°S and 35°S.
[src:anticucho/andes] In this area, the angle of subduction is very low, meaning the subducting plate is nearly horizontal.
[src:anticucho/andes] Studies of mantle hydration across the subduction zone have shown a correlation between increased material hydration and lower-magnitude, more frequent seismic activity.
[src:anticucho/andes] Zones exhibiting dehydration instead are thought to have a higher potential for larger, high-magnitude earthquakes in the future.
[src:anticucho/andes] The mountain range is also a source of shallow intraplate earthquakes within the South American Plate.
[src:anticucho/andes] The largest such earthquake (as of 2024) struck Peru in 1947 and measured Ms 7.5.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the Peruvian Andes, these earthquakes display normal (1946), strike-slip (1976), and reverse (1969, 1983) mechanisms.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Amazonian Craton is actively underthrusted beneath the sub-Andes region of Peru, producing thrust faults.
[src:anticucho/andes] In Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru, thrust faulting occurs along the sub-Andes due in response to contraction brought on by subduction, while in the high Andes, normal faulting occurs in response to gravitational forces.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the extreme south, a major transform fault separates Tierra del Fuego from the small Scotia Plate.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes range has many active volcanoes distributed in four volcanic zones separated by areas of inactivity.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andean volcanism is a result of the subduction of the Nazca Plate and Antarctic Plate underneath the South American Plate.
[src:anticucho/andes] The belt is subdivided into four main volcanic zones that are separated from each other by volcanic gaps.
[src:anticucho/andes] The volcanoes of the belt are diverse in terms of activity style, products, and morphology.
[src:anticucho/andes] Although some differences can be explained by which volcanic zone a volcano belongs to, there are significant differences inside volcanic zones and even between neighboring volcanoes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes Mountains host large ore and salt deposits, and some of their eastern fold and thrust belts act as traps for commercially exploitable amounts of hydrocarbons.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the forelands of the Atacama Desert, some of the largest porphyry copper mineralizations occur, making Chile and Peru the first- and second-largest exporters of copper in the world.
[src:anticucho/andes] Porphyry copper in the western slopes of the Andes has been generated by hydrothermal fluids (mostly water) during the cooling of plutons or volcanic systems.
[src:anticucho/andes] The porphyry mineralization further benefited from the dry climate that reduced the disturbing actions of meteoric water.
[src:anticucho/andes] The dry climate in the central western Andes has also led to the creation of extensive saltpeter deposits that were extensively mined until the invention of synthetic nitrates.
[src:anticucho/andes] Yet another result of the dry climate are the salars of Atacama and Uyuni, the former being the largest source of lithium and the latter the world's largest reserve of the element.
[src:anticucho/andes] Early Mesozoic and Neogene plutonism in Bolivia's Cordillera Central created the Bolivian tin belt as well as the famous, now mostly depleted, silver deposits of Cerro Rico de Potosí.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes Mountains is connected to the climate of South America, particularly through the hyper-arid conditions of the adjacent Atacama Desert.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Atacama Bench, a prominent low-relief feature along the Pacific seaboard, serves as a key geomorphological record of the long-term interplay between Andean tectonics and Cenozoic climate.
[src:anticucho/andes] While the initial uplift and shortening of the Andes were driven by the subduction of the Nazca Plate beneath the South American Plate, arid climate acted as an important feedback mechanism.
[src:anticucho/andes] Reduced erosion rates in the increasingly arid Atacama region may have effectively stopped tectonic activity in certain parts of the mountain range.
[src:anticucho/andes] This lack of erosion could have facilitated the eastward propagation of deformation, leading to the widening of the Andean orogen over time.
[src:anticucho/andes] Thus, the Atacama Desert and its geological features, like the Atacama Bench, offer critical insights into the coupled evolution of the Andes Mountains and the changing regional climate.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes Mountains, initially inhabited by hunter-gatherers, experienced the development of agriculture and the rise of politically centralized civilizations, which culminated in the establishment of the century-long Inca Empire.
[src:anticucho/andes] This all changed in the 16th century, when the Spanish conquistadors colonized the mountains in advance of the mining economy.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the tide of anti-imperialist nationalism, the Andes became the scene of a series of independence wars in the 19th century, when rebel forces swept through the region to overthrow Spanish colonial rule.
[src:anticucho/andes] Since then, many former Spanish territories have become five independent Andean states.
[src:anticucho/andes] The climate in the Andes varies greatly depending on latitude, altitude, and proximity to the sea.
[src:anticucho/andes] Temperature, atmospheric pressure, and humidity decrease in higher elevations.
[src:anticucho/andes] The southern section is rainy and cool, while the central section is dry.
[src:anticucho/andes] The northern Andes are typically rainy and warm, with an average temperature of 18 °C (64 °F) in Colombia.
[src:anticucho/andes] The climate is known to change drastically in rather short distances.
[src:anticucho/andes] Rainforests exist just kilometers away from the snow-covered peak of Cotopaxi.
[src:anticucho/andes] The mountains have a large effect on the temperatures of nearby areas.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes of Chile and Argentina can be divided into two climatic and glaciological zones: the Dry Andes and the Wet Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] Since the Dry Andes extend from the latitudes of the Atacama Desert to the area of the Maule River, precipitation is more sporadic, and there are strong temperature oscillations.
[src:anticucho/andes] The line of equilibrium may shift drastically over short periods of time, leaving a whole glacier in the ablation area or in the accumulation area.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the high Andes of Central Chile and Mendoza Province, rock glaciers are larger and more common than glaciers; this is due to the high exposure to solar radiation.
[src:anticucho/andes] In these regions, glaciers occur typically at higher altitudes than rock glaciers.
[src:anticucho/andes] The lowest active rock glaciers occur at 900 m a.s.l. in Aconcagua.
[src:anticucho/andes] Though precipitation increases with height, there are semiarid conditions in the nearly 7,000-metre (22,966 ft) highest mountains of the Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] This dry steppe climate is considered to be typical of the subtropical position at 32–34° S.
[src:anticucho/andes] The valley bottoms have no woods, just dwarf scrub.
[src:anticucho/andes] The largest glaciers, for example the Plomo Glacier and the Horcones Glaciers, do not even reach 10 km (6.2 mi) in length and have only insignificant ice thickness.
[src:anticucho/andes] 20,000 years ago, the glaciers were over ten times longer.
[src:anticucho/andes] On the east side of this section of the Mendozina Andes, they flowed down to 2,060 m (6,760 ft) and on the west side to about 1,220 m (4,000 ft) above sea level.
[src:anticucho/andes] The massifs of Aconcagua (6,961 m or 22,838 ft), Tupungato (6,550 m or 21,490 ft), and Nevado Juncal (6,110 m or 20,050 ft) are tens of kilometres away from each other and were connected by a joint ice stream network.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes' dendritic glacier arms, components of valley glaciers, were up to 112.5 km (69.9 mi) long and over 1,250 m (4,100 ft) thick, and spanned a vertical distance of 5,150 m (16,900 ft).
[src:anticucho/andes] The climatic glacier snowline (ELA) was lowered from 4,600 m (15,100 ft) to 3,200 m (10,500 ft) at glacial times.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andean region cuts across several natural and floristic regions, due to its extension, from Caribbean Venezuela to cold, windy, and wet Cape Horn passing through the hyperarid Atacama Desert.
[src:anticucho/andes] Rainforests and tropical dry forests used to encircle much of the northern Andes but are now greatly diminished, especially in the Chocó and inter-Andean valleys of Colombia.
[src:anticucho/andes] Opposite the humid Andean slopes are the relatively dry Andean slopes in most of western Peru, Chile, and Argentina.
[src:anticucho/andes] Along with several Interandean Valles, they are typically dominated by deciduous woodland, shrub and xeric vegetation, reaching the extreme in the slopes near the virtually lifeless Atacama Desert.
[src:anticucho/andes] About 30,000 species of vascular plants live in the Andes, with roughly half being endemic to the region, surpassing the diversity of any other hotspot.
[src:anticucho/andes] The small tree *Cinchona pubescens*, a source of quinine that is used to treat malaria, is found widely in the Andes as far south as Bolivia.
[src:anticucho/andes] Other important crops that originated from the Andes are tobacco and potatoes.
[src:anticucho/andes] The high-altitude *Polylepis* forests and woodlands are found in the Andean areas of Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, and Chile.
[src:anticucho/andes] These trees, by locals referred to as Queñua, Yagual, and other names, can be found at altitudes of 4,500 m (14,760 ft) above sea level.
[src:anticucho/andes] It remains unclear if the patchy distribution of these forests and woodlands is natural, or the result of clearing that began during the Incan period.
[src:anticucho/andes] Regardless, in modern times, the clearance has accelerated, and the trees are now considered highly endangered, with some believing that as little as 10% of the original woodland remains.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes are rich in fauna: With almost 1,000 species, of which roughly 2/3 are endemic to the region, the Andes are the most important region in the world for amphibians.
[src:anticucho/andes] The diversity of animals in the Andes is high, with almost 600 species of mammals (13% endemic), more than 1,700 species of birds (about 1/3 endemic), more than 600 species of reptiles (about 45% endemic), and almost 400 species of fish (about 1/3 endemic).
[src:anticucho/andes] The vicuña and guanaco can be found living in the Altiplano, while the closely related domesticated llama and alpaca are widely kept by locals as pack animals and for their meat and wool.
[src:anticucho/andes] The crepuscular (active during dawn and dusk) chinchillas, two threatened members of the rodent order, inhabit the Andes' alpine regions.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andean condor, the largest bird of its kind in the Western Hemisphere, occurs throughout much of the Andes but generally in very low densities.
[src:anticucho/andes] Lake Titicaca hosts several endemics, among them the highly endangered Titicaca flightless grebe and Titicaca water frog.
[src:anticucho/andes] These forest-types, which includes the Yungas and parts of the Chocó, are very rich in flora and fauna, although few large mammals exist, exceptions being the threatened mountain tapir, spectacled bear, and yellow-tailed woolly monkey.
[src:anticucho/andes] Birds of humid Andean forests include mountain toucans, quetzals, and the Andean cock-of-the-rock, while mixed-species flocks dominated by tanagers and furnariids are commonly seen—in contrast to several vocal but typically cryptic species of wrens, tapaculos, and antpittas.
[src:anticucho/andes] A number of species such as the royal cinclodes and white-browed tit-spinetail are associated with *Polylepis*, and consequently also threatened.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes Mountains form a north–south axis of cultural influences.
[src:anticucho/andes] A long series of cultural development culminated in the expansion of the Inca civilization and Inca Empire in the central Andes during the 15th century.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Incas formed this civilization through imperialistic militarism as well as careful and meticulous governmental management.
[src:anticucho/andes] The government sponsored the construction of aqueducts and roads in addition to pre-existing installations.
[src:anticucho/andes] Some of these constructions still exist today.
[src:anticucho/andes] Devastated by European diseases and by civil war, the Incas were defeated in 1532 by an alliance composed of tens of thousands of allies from nations they had subjugated (e.g.
[src:anticucho/andes] Huancas, Chachapoyas, Cañaris) and a small army of 180 Spaniards led by Francisco Pizarro.
[src:anticucho/andes] One of the few Inca sites the Spanish never found in their conquest was Machu Picchu, which lay hidden on a peak on the eastern edge of the Andes where they descend to the Amazon.
[src:anticucho/andes] The main surviving languages of the Andean peoples are those of the Quechua and Aymara language families.
[src:anticucho/andes] Woodbine Parish and Joseph Barclay Pentland surveyed a large part of the Bolivian Andes from 1826 to 1827.
[src:anticucho/andes] In modern times, the largest cities in the Andes are Bogotá, with a metropolitan population of over ten million, and Santiago, Medellín, Cali, and Quito.
[src:anticucho/andes] Lima is a coastal city adjacent to the Andes and is the largest city of all Andean countries.
[src:anticucho/andes] It is the seat of the Andean Community of Nations.
[src:anticucho/andes] La Paz, Bolivia's seat of government, is the highest capital city in the world, at an elevation of approximately 3,650 m (11,975 ft).
[src:anticucho/andes] Parts of the La Paz conurbation, including the city of El Alto, extend up to 4,200 m (13,780 ft).
[src:anticucho/andes] The cities of Caracas, Valencia, and Maracay are in the Venezuelan Coastal Range, which is a debatable extension of the Andes at the northern extremity of South America.
[src:anticucho/andes] Cities and large towns are connected with asphalt-paved roads, while smaller towns are often connected by dirt roads, which may require a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
[src:anticucho/andes] The rough terrain has historically put the costs of building highways and railroads that cross the Andes out of reach of most neighboring countries, even with modern civil engineering practices.
[src:anticucho/andes] For example, the main crossover of the Andes between Argentina and Chile is still accomplished through the Paso Internacional Los Libertadores.
[src:anticucho/andes] Only recently have the ends of some highways that came rather close to one another from the east and the west been connected.
[src:anticucho/andes] Much of the transportation of passengers is done via aircraft.
[src:anticucho/andes] There is one railroad that connects Chile with Peru via the Andes, however, and there are others that make the same connection via southern Bolivia.
[src:anticucho/andes] There are multiple highways in Bolivia that cross the Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] Some of these were built during a period of war between Bolivia and Paraguay, in order to transport Bolivian troops and their supplies to the war front in the lowlands of southeastern Bolivia and western Paraguay.
[src:anticucho/andes] For decades, Chile claimed ownership of land on the eastern side of the Andes.
[src:anticucho/andes] These claims were given up in about 1870 during the War of the Pacific between Chile and the allied Bolivia and Peru, in a diplomatic deal to keep Peru out of the war.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Chilean Army and Chilean Navy defeated the combined forces of Bolivia and Peru, and Chile took over Bolivia's only province on the Pacific Coast, some land from Peru that was returned to Peru decades later.
[src:anticucho/andes] Bolivia has been completely landlocked ever since.
[src:anticucho/andes] It mostly uses seaports in eastern Argentina and Uruguay for international trade because its diplomatic relations with Chile have been suspended since 1978.
[src:anticucho/andes] Because of the tortuous terrain in places, villages and towns in the mountains—to which travel via motorized vehicles is of little use—are still located in the high Andes of Chile, Bolivia, Peru, and Ecuador.
[src:anticucho/andes] Locally, the relatives of the camel, the llama, and the alpaca continue to carry out important uses as pack animals, but this use has generally diminished in modern times.
[src:anticucho/andes] Donkeys, mules, and horses are also useful.
[src:anticucho/andes] The ancient peoples of the Andes such as the Incas have practiced irrigation techniques for over 6,000 years.
[src:anticucho/andes] Because of the mountain slopes, terracing has been a common practice.
[src:anticucho/andes] Terracing, however, was only extensively employed after Incan imperial expansions to fuel their expanding realm.
[src:anticucho/andes] The potato holds a very important role as an internally consumed staple crop.
[src:anticucho/andes] Maize was also an important crop for these people, and was used for the production of chicha, important to Andean native people.
[src:anticucho/andes] Currently, tobacco, cotton, quinoa, and coffee are the main export crops.
[src:anticucho/andes] Coca, despite eradication programs in some countries, remains an important crop for legal local use in a mildly stimulating herbal tea, and illegally for the production of cocaine.
[src:anticucho/andes] In unirrigated land, pasture is the most common type of land use.
[src:anticucho/andes] In the rainy season (summer), part of the rangeland is used for cropping (mainly potatoes, barley, broad beans, and wheat).
[src:anticucho/andes] Irrigation is helpful in advancing the sowing data of the summer crops, which guarantees an early yield in periods of food shortage.
[src:anticucho/andes] Also, by early sowing, maize can be cultivated higher up in the mountains (up to 3,800 m (12,500 ft)).
[src:anticucho/andes] In addition, it makes cropping in the dry season (winter) possible and allows the cultivation of frost-resistant vegetable crops like onion and carrot.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes rose to fame for their mineral wealth during the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:anticucho/andes] Although Andean Amerindian peoples crafted ceremonial jewelry of gold and other metals, the mineralizations of the Andes were first mined on a large scale after the Spanish arrival.
[src:anticucho/andes] Potosí in present-day Bolivia and Cerro de Pasco in Peru were among the principal mines of the Spanish Empire in the New World.
[src:anticucho/andes] Río de la Plata and Argentina derive their names from the silver of Potosí.
[src:anticucho/andes] Currently, mining in the Andes of Chile and Peru places these countries as the first and second major producers of copper in the world.
[src:anticucho/andes] Peru also contains the 4th-largest goldmine in the world: the Yanacocha.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Bolivian Andes principally produce tin, although historically silver mining had a huge impact on the economy of 17th-century Europe.
[src:anticucho/andes] In Chile in the higher portions of the Andes there are only mining districs dominated by large-scale mining, while medium and small-scale mining is more common at lower altitudes.
[src:anticucho/andes] For mines in the high Andes there are logistical difficulties in the use of sea water, in addition to increased probabilities of extreme weather events that may disrupt water supply.
[src:anticucho/andes] The gold deposits of the El Indio Gold Belt tend to lie along the Argentina–Chile border and next to or below glaciers and gold mining there have thus issues relating to the bi-nationality and their environmental impacts on glaciers.
[src:anticucho/andes] Mining in the cold conditions in the Andes pose also difficult conditions for outdoor workers such as pallaqueras and for the batteries of electrified machinery.
[src:anticucho/andes] There is a long history of mining in the Andes, from the Spanish silver mines in Potosí in the 16th century to the vast current porphyry copper deposits of Chuquicamata and Escondida in Chile and Toquepala in Peru.
[src:anticucho/andes] Other metals, including iron, gold, and tin, in addition to non-metallic resources are important.
[src:anticucho/andes] The Andes have a vast supply of lithium; Argentina, Bolivia, and Chile have the three largest reserves in the world respectively.
[src:anticucho/andes] This list contains some of the major peaks in the Andes mountain range.
[src:anticucho/andes] The highest peak is Aconcagua of Argentina.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Anticuchos can be found on street-carts and street food stalls (*anticucheras*).
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The meat may be marinated in vinegar and spices (such as cumin, ají pepper and garlic).
[src:anticucho/anticucho] While anticuchos can be made of any type of meat, the most popular are made of beef heart (*anticuchos de corazón*).
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Anticuchos usually come with a boiled potato at the end of the skewer.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] A similar dish, shish kebab, is found in Mediterranean cuisine.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] In Peru, anticuchos are linked to the procession of Señor de los Milagros.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] In the 16th century European ingredients such as garlic were added and beef began to replace the traditional llama that was used at the time of the Inca Empire.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] It was a popular dish among the inhabitants of the Inca Empire, and it is currently popular throughout most South American countries.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Americanized versions of anticuchos are sometimes made of non-organ meats.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] According to the text file from the National Library in Lima (Peru), it is believed that the term comes from the Quechua *antikuchu* (*anti*: 'East' + *kuchu*: 'cut' or *uchu*: 'porridge, mix').
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The writer Erika Fetzer mentions that according to tradition, anticuchos were prepared with meat and flame.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The Spanish strung the meat on sticks as skewers.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The Spaniards also brought enslaved Africans, who were concentrated in Lima and the coast of southern Peru of the Vice-royalty of Peru.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] In those days, the Spanish dismissed offal as food for slaves; the Spanish generally cooked with the "prime" cuts only.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] As a result, many traditional recipes use beef heart and other "off" cuts.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] In Peru, the tradition continues with the traditional name and ingredients; anticuchos are consumed by all social classes of Peru, and are especially popular as a street food.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Traditional anticuchos are made with beef heart slivers ranging from 2 cm x 2 cm to about 5 cm × 5 cm, roasted on a metal skewer about 30 to 40 cm (16 in) long and 3 × 3 mm in diameter.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] They are seasoned with salt to taste, and sometimes with vinegar.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] A popular dressing is a sauce made from garlic, onion, aji panca, cumin, black pepper, and beer, which is spread onto the anticuchos while cooking.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Anticuchos are usually not the main course of a meal, but rather an accompaniment to grilled meats along with other side dishes such as choripanes, potatoes, sausages and salads.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Anticuchos are part of traditional Peruvian cuisine.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The greatest consumption in Peru is in July, during the celebration of *Fiestas Patrias* (Independence Day) in fondas and BBQs.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The Bolivian anticucho is a dish based on thin beef heart fillets marinated in spices, oil, and vinegar, cooked on skewers and over charcoal, and then served hot, mainly accompanied by roast potatoes and spicy sauce or peanut llajua.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The anticucho is widely known as one of the favorite night delicacies dishes in innumerable parts of Bolivia.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] The vendors (affectionately known as "anticucheras") are easy to find on streets or boulevards and have a peculiar ritual to attract their clients, which consists of creating spectacular flames of fire that give off the irresistible aroma of the dish.
[src:anticucho/anticucho] Known as "chuzos" in the Sierra Region and "carne en palito" in the Costa Region, they are a favorite night street food.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Antisuyu is the second smallest of the *suyus**.* It was located northeast of Cusco in the high Andes.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Indeed, it is the root of the word "Andes".
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] 'Anti' is the likely origin of the word 'Andes', Spanish conquerors generalized the term and named all the mountain chain as 'Andes', instead of only the eastern region, as it was the case in Inca era.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] According to some sources, Antisuyu was not the smallest of the Incan *suyus*, citing that its territory may have included the eastern slope of the Tahuantinsuyu as well as the adjoining tropical lowlands along the length of the empire.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Antisuyu and Chinchaysuyu were bordered by a line west of the Inca road that ran from Cusco to Tambomachay.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] The *suyu* was also separated from Collasuyu by the Huatanay River, which flowed through the city to the eastern end of the valley.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Most of the lowland jungle was not part of Tawantinsuyu.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Only the jungle region could not be dominated by the Incas, given that they could not colonize the jungle region.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] After subjugating the Ch'unchus, very few arrived at Musu.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] The region of Antisuyu was the final retreat of the Neo-Inca state as they fled Spanish conquest.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Notable among the Inca settlements here were Vilcabamba, and Vitcos.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] It is also thought that the mythical city of Paititi may exist somewhere within this region.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Historian Andrew Nicol published research in 2009 in which he concluded that the existence of a city such as Paititi is possible within the Peruvian Amazon Basin.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Research as recent as 2016 by Vincent Pélissier provides a possible location for the lost city to the northeast of Vilcabamba.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Antisuyu was previously not part of the Incan empire.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] It was later conquered to address the problem of the shrinking space for crops along the coastal region of the empire.
[src:anticucho/antisuyu] Each *suyu* was divided into *wamani*, or provinces.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The invention has been attributed, though without evidence, to Zuo Zongtang, a military leader of the late Qing dynasty.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] In 1855, the army of the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom invaded the Fujian region and General Zuo was appointed to lead an army to crush the rebels.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The recipe does seem to have spread throughout the Fujian region, especially around Quanzhou and later on throughout Southeast China.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] It was brought south into Southeast Asia or Nanyang by Hokkien and Teochew immigrants, especially to Singapore, and merchants spread it to neighbouring regions.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] In Indonesia, this dish originated in Bangka Belitung Islands by ethnic Chinese (Hokkien and Khek) and it was named “Hok Lo Pan” which translates to “Hoklo ethnicity’s cake.” Its traditional topping includes sugar and sesame seeds.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] Martabak manis have different names in different regions.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] In West Borneo, it is called *apam pinang*, similar to Malaysia's *apam balik*.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] In Central Java, *martabak manis* is referred to as *kue Bandung* which means Bandung cake.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The origin of *kue Bandung* started when a man from Bangka Belitung, opened a Martabak manis stall beside a “Bandung Noodle” stall.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The dessert is also known by various names in different languages, depending on the region.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The pancake's batter is made from a mixture of flour, eggs, sugar, baking soda, coconut milk and water.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The batter is cooked upon a thick round iron frying pan in plenty of palm margarine to avoid it sticking to the pan.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] Then other ingredients are sprinkled as filling; the most common or traditional is crushed peanut granules with sugar and sweetcorn kernels (available from cans), but modern innovations such as chocolate sprinkles and cheddar cheese are also available.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] Then, the pancake is folded (hence the name: "turnover pancake") and cut into several pieces.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] In Indonesia there is a smaller version made with smaller pan, they are called *martabak mini* or *terang bulan mini*.
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] The texture of the apam balik can vary depending on the amount of batter and type of pan used, from one that is akin to a crispier form of crumpets to small thin light pancake shells that break when bitten (the latter is usually called *apam balik nipis*, 'thin apam balik').
[src:anticucho/apam-balik] There is a Peranakan variant, the *apom balik*, that closely resembles the Indonesian *Serabi*.
